The paper discusses the use of information geometry in the context of probability distributions and estimation theory, which suggests that it could fall under several sub-categories. Specifically, cs.IT (Information Theory) is a likely category given the focus on the Fisher Information Matrix and the proposed Riemannian metric. cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.ST (Statistics) are also likely categories given the emphasis on estimation theory and the Cram\'{e}r-Rao lower bound. cs.SY (Systems and Control) and cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) are less likely but still possible categories given the potential applications of the proposed approach to practical systems.
